                                             -Cohen and Lichter<br>
<br>
“If nuclear power were clean, safe, economic, assured of ample fuel, and socially benign per se, it would still be unattractive because of the political implications of the kind of energy economy it would lock us into.”<br>
                                               - Amory Lovins<br>
<br>
“What then has happened to science? … With a weakened certainty about objectivity, people find it easier to come to whatever conclusions they desire for the sociological ends they wish to see achieved … this is what I call sociological science: choices being made on the basis of the sociological consequences which would result … the ideal of objectivity in science is weakened.”<br>
                                          -Francis Schaeffer<br>
<br>
Lovins was one of the founders of the renewible energy movement, fostering the idea that we could survive on 'low tech' renewibles alone. Nuclear power epitimizes the high tech, large scale energy industry, the antithesis of such writers as Lovins and EF Schmmacher's vision of a movement toward a smaller scaled more sustainible society. Big generating stations just don't fit in. In Cohen and Lichter's study on the opinions of major decision makers, scientists, environmentalists, politicians, etc., the enviromentalists did not have any specific safety issues they felt were more important with nuclear energy, they replied they had strong conserns with everything to do with it. Cohen and Licher concluded that this may suggest they were simply against the idea altogether, with their arguments against safety issues more of a side effect. This may be why they do not attack coal as they do nuclear, although it presents a much greater environmental risk it does not represent the same 'high tech' idiological challage.<br>
<br>
This is not to say that all environmentalists are antitechnology or guilty of &quot;sociological science&quot;, that is clearly not the case as there are informed ones as well.<br>
<br>
